That is a top-tier minimalist stack. Since you are using Ghostty (which has excellent rendering) and Hyprland, you have two main ways to "view markdown nicely": rendering it directly in the terminal buffer or previewing it in a synchronized browser window.

Here are the best options for your specific setup in 2026:

1. The "In-Editor" Experience (Best for Ghostty)
If you want to keep everything inside your terminal without opening a browser, render-markdown.nvim is the current gold standard. It uses Tree-sitter to "conceal" the markdown syntax and replace it with high-quality UI elements.

What it does: Converts ### into heading icons, - [ ] into interactive checkboxes, and | table | into clean, bordered boxes—all while you are still in the buffer.

Why it fits you: Since Ghostty supports modern terminal features (like Nerd Fonts and undercurls), this looks incredibly native.

Plugin: MeanderingProgrammer/render-markdown.nvim

2. The "Live Browser" Experience (Classic)
If you need to see exactly how a README will look on GitHub, or if you have complex LaTeX/Mermaid diagrams, markdown-preview.nvim is the go-to.

What it does: It opens a local port and syncs your Neovim buffer to a browser tab. As you scroll in Neovim, the browser scrolls with you.

Hyprland Tip: You can use a Hyprland "window rule" to automatically tile your browser next to Ghostty when the preview starts.

Plugin: iamcco/markdown-preview.nvim

3. The "Fancy UI" Alternative
If you find render-markdown too minimal, markview.nvim is a newer, more "opinionated" plugin that aims to make Neovim feel almost like a dedicated Markdown editor (similar to Obsidian).

Feature: It has a very polished look for code blocks and horizontal rules.

Plugin: OXY2DEV/markview.nvim

